<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="103" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="103">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="103">
<taxonomicName authority="K.Romaschenko, P.M.Peterson &amp; R.J.Soreng, 2019" authorityName="K.Romaschenko, P.M.Peterson &amp; R.J.Soreng" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Ptilagrostiella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ptilagrostiella kingii" order="Poales" pageId="14" pageNumber="103" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kingii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="103">Ptilagrostiella kingii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to California known only in the Sierra Nevada (Fresno, Inyo, Madera, Mariposa, Mono, Tulare, and Tuolomne counties) and is associated with lodgepole and subalpine forests (
<bibRefCitation author="Calflora" journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington, D. C." pageId="20" pageNumber="109" publicationUrl="https://www.calflora.org/" refId="B5" refString="Calflora, 2018. Information on California plants for education, research and conservation. Berkeley, California: The Calflora Database (a non-profit organization). https://www.calflora.org/" title="Information on California plants for education, research and conservation. Berkeley, California: The Calflora Database (a non-profit organization)." url="https://www.calflora.org/" year="2018">Calflora 2018</bibRefCitation>
). The species grows along moist streambanks and open, wet to dry meadows; 2000-3650 m (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2418359" author="Barkworth, ME" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany" pageId="20" pageNumber="109" pagination="395 - 419" refId="B2" refString="Barkworth, ME, 1983. Ptilagrostis in North America and its relationship to other Stipeae. Systematic Botany 8 (4): 395 - 419, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/2418359" title="Ptilagrostis in North America and its relationship to other Stipeae." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2418359" volume="8" year="1983">Barkworth 1983</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Barkworth, ME" editor="Barkworth, ME" journalOrPublisher="Oxford Universtiy Press, New York" pageId="20" pageNumber="109" pagination="109 - 186" refId="B3" refString="Barkworth, ME, 2007. 10. Stipeae Dumort. In: Barkworth, ME, Capels, KM, Long, S, Anderton, LK, Piep, MB, Eds., Magnoliophyta: Commelinidae (in part): Poaceae, part 1. Oxford Universtiy Press, New York: 109 - 186" title="10. Stipeae Dumort." volumeTitle="Magnoliophyta: Commelinidae (in part): Poaceae, part 1." year="2007">2007</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="104" pageId="14" pageNumber="103" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="103">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="104" pageId="14" pageNumber="103">
In our earlier molecular analysis, 
<taxonomicName authority="K.Romaschenko, P.M.Peterson &amp; R.J.Soreng, 2019" authorityName="K.Romaschenko, P.M.Peterson &amp; R.J.Soreng" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Ptilagrostiella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ptilagrostiella kingii" order="Poales" pageId="14" pageNumber="103" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kingii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="103">Ptilagrostiella kingii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sister to a well-supported clade of 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Piptatheropsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Piptatheropsis" order="Poales" pageId="14" pageNumber="103" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="103">Piptatheropsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.606015" author="Romaschenko, K" journalOrPublisher="Aarhus University Press, Denmark" pageId="22" pageNumber="111" refId="B25" refString="Romaschenko, K, Peterson, PM, Soreng, RJ, Futorna, O, Susanna, A, 2011. Phylogenetics of Piptatherum s.l. (Poaceae: Stipeae): Evidence for a new genus, Piptatheropsis, and resurrection of Patis. Taxon 60(6): 1703-1716. https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.606015" title="Phylogenetics of Piptatherum s. l. (Poaceae: Stipeae): Evidence for a new genus, Piptatheropsis, and resurrection of Patis. Taxon 60 (6): 1703 - 1716." url="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.606015" year="2011">Romaschenko et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.611002" author="Romaschenko, K" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="22" pageNumber="111" pagination="18 - 44" refId="B26" refString="Romaschenko, K, Peterson, PM, Soreng, RJ, Garcia-Jacas, N, Futorna, O, Susanna, A, 2012. Systematics and evolution of the needle grasses (Poaceae: Pooideae: Stipeae) based on analysis of multiple chloroplast loci, ITS, and lemma micromorphology. Taxon 61 (1): 18 - 44, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.611002" title="Systematics and evolution of the needle grasses (Poaceae: Pooideae: Stipeae) based on analysis of multiple chloroplast loci, ITS, and lemma micromorphology." url="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.611002" volume="61" year="2012">2012</bibRefCitation>
). As indicated by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2418359" author="Barkworth, ME" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany" pageId="20" pageNumber="109" pagination="395 - 419" refId="B2" refString="Barkworth, ME, 1983. Ptilagrostis in North America and its relationship to other Stipeae. Systematic Botany 8 (4): 395 - 419, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/2418359" title="Ptilagrostis in North America and its relationship to other Stipeae." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2418359" volume="8" year="1983">
<pageBreakToken pageId="15" pageNumber="104" start="start">Barkworth</pageBreakToken>
(1983)
</bibRefCitation>
, the similarities between 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. kingii" pageId="15" pageNumber="104" rank="species" species="kingii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="104">P. kingii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Gramineae" genus="Ptilagrostis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ptilagrostis" order="Poales" pageId="15" pageNumber="104" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="104">Ptilagrostis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may have resulted from convergent evolution in distantly related taxa growing under similar environmental conditions since the former species shares an immediate common ancestor with 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Piptatheropsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Piptatheropsis" order="Poales" pageId="15" pageNumber="104" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="104">Piptatheropsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and does not align near the 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Gramineae" genus="Ptilagrostis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ptilagrostis" order="Poales" pageId="15" pageNumber="104" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="104">Ptilagrostis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clade (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.611002" author="Romaschenko, K" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="22" pageNumber="111" pagination="18 - 44" refId="B26" refString="Romaschenko, K, Peterson, PM, Soreng, RJ, Garcia-Jacas, N, Futorna, O, Susanna, A, 2012. Systematics and evolution of the needle grasses (Poaceae: Pooideae: Stipeae) based on analysis of multiple chloroplast loci, ITS, and lemma micromorphology. Taxon 61 (1): 18 - 44, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.611002" title="Systematics and evolution of the needle grasses (Poaceae: Pooideae: Stipeae) based on analysis of multiple chloroplast loci, ITS, and lemma micromorphology." url="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.611002" volume="61" year="2012">Romaschenko et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="K.Romaschenko, P.M.Peterson &amp; R.J.Soreng, 2019" authorityName="K.Romaschenko, P.M.Peterson &amp; R.J.Soreng" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Ptilagrostiella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ptilagrostiella kingii" order="Poales" pageId="15" pageNumber="104" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kingii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="104">Ptilagrostiella kingii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also lacks a blunt callus and the plumose awns characteristic of most 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Gramineae" genus="Ptilagrostis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ptilagrostis" order="Poales" pageId="15" pageNumber="104" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="104">Ptilagrostis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (
<bibRefCitation author="Wu, ZL" editor="Wu, Z" journalOrPublisher="Science Press and Missouri Botanical Garden Press, Beijing and St. Louis" pageId="23" pageNumber="112" pagination="188 - 212" refId="B46" refString="Wu, ZL, Phillips, SM, 2006. 7. Tribe Stipeae. In: Wu, Z, Raven, PH, Hong, DY, Eds., Flora of China, Poaceae. Science Press and Missouri Botanical Garden Press, Beijing and St. Louis: 188 - 212" title="7. Tribe Stipeae." volumeTitle="Flora of China, Poaceae." year="2006">Wu and Phillips 2006</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
